    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/gcbp-experimental-piv-vad-baseline",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/gcbp-operating-envelope-cpb-5points"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis QoI validation — RH index across 5 CPB operating points",
      "description": "The CFD model was exercised across the five nominated CPB flow-speed combinations (2.5 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3.5 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4.5 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5.0 L/min at 3800 RPM, and 5.5 L/min at 4000 RPM). Predicted normalised hemolysis index values ranged from 0.61 to 0.94, all satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. Mesh-independence was confirmed at 8.2 M cells (GCI < 2.1% for all operating points). The power-law hemolysis damage model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger coefficients) was applied consistently. Solver residuals converged to below 1e-5 for all continuity and momentum equations. The validation narrative notes that prior published benchmarking of this model class against experimental hemolysis data demonstrates good predictive fidelity, and the team is satisfied that the model captures the dominant shear-stress-driven damage mechanism relevant to CPB conditions. No quantitative discordance metric against a specific experimental reference dataset is reported for this operating envelope because the experimental campaign is ongoing; interim confidence is drawn from the convergence indicators and the qualitative agreement described in the secondary validation result below."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vad-piv-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary velocity-field validation against PIV benchmark — VAD baseline conditions",
      "description": "Particle image velocimetry (PIV) measurements from the FDA-sponsored interlaboratory study (Hariharan et al. 2011) were used as the experimental comparator for velocity field validation. The CFD model reproduced the measured axial and radial velocity profiles in the pump outlet region with a mean absolute error of 4.3% and a maximum pointwise deviation of 11.7% at the impeller tip. These results are considered strong evidence of model fidelity. The PIV dataset was acquired at 2.5 L/min and 3500 RPM — conditions representative of the VAD operating envelope used in the original FDA benchmark exercise. The validation team noted that these conditions overlap substantially with the lower end of the CPB operating range specified in this COU, and concluded that the velocity-field accuracy demonstrated here supports confidence in the hemolysis predictions across the full CPB envelope.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/gcbp-experimental-piv-vad-baseline",
      "quantitativeMetric": "Mean absolute velocity error 4.3%; max pointwise deviation 11.7%",
      "validationActivity": "Comparison of CFD-predicted velocity profiles against PIV measurements from Hariharan et al. 2011 FDA interlaboratory benchmark",
      "assessorNote": "Comparator dataset was collected under VAD duty-cycle conditions (continuous flow at fixed 3500 RPM, haematocrit 0%, glycerol-water analogue fluid). CPB operating conditions in this COU include pulsatile-assist modes, full blood viscosity, and RPM sweep from 2500 to 4000. The single-speed, analogue-fluid VAD benchmark does not replicate the viscosity-dependent shear thinning or the RPM-dependent secondary flow structures that govern worst-case hemolysis identification under CPB conditions. This distinction is not examined in the validation narrative above."
    }
  ],
