      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted at 3.5 L/min, 3000 RPM. Mesh sizes of 3.1 M, 8.2 M, and 18.6 M cells yielded GCI values of 8.7%, 2.1%, and — respectively for the hemolysis index QoI. The 8.2 M cell mesh was selected as the production mesh, achieving GCI < 2.1% and satisfying the Gradation 2 threshold. The same mesh topology was applied to all five operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation activities must be documented and shown to overlap with the COU operating envelope at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "The PIV benchmark conditions (2.5 L/min, 3500 RPM, glycerol-water analogue) are documented in Hariharan et al. 2011. The validation team assessed these as partially overlapping with the CPB COU operating envelope. The lower bound of the CPB flow range (2.5 L/min) coincides with the PIV test point, which was judged sufficient to satisfy Gradation 2 for this factor at MRL 2. The differences in fluid rheology and rotational speed range were noted but not treated as disqualifying."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric between model outputs and experimental data reported with uncertainty bounds at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Velocity field comparisons against the PIV dataset yielded mean absolute error of 4.3% and maximum pointwise deviation of 11.7%. These metrics are within the acceptance band established for Gradation 2 output comparison. Uncertainty in the PIV measurements (estimated ±3.5% by Hariharan et al.) was accounted for in the error metric calculation. The hemolysis index comparison against a dedicated CPB experimental dataset was deferred pending completion of the ongoing experimental campaign."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation activities must be shown to be relevant surrogates for the COU decision QoI (worst-case hemolysis identification) at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Velocity field accuracy is a necessary but not sufficient condition for hemolysis prediction accuracy, as the power-law damage model depends on local shear stress derived from velocity gradients. The validation team argued that accurate velocity field reproduction implies adequate shear stress field accuracy, and therefore that velocity QoIs are relevant surrogates for the hemolysis index QoI at Gradation 2. This inference was accepted without sensitivity analysis of the damage model coefficients."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
